<p>You signed up for broadband at £28 a month. Two years later, you're paying £42. You didn't switch providers. You didn't upgrade your speed. You just stopped checking.</p>

<p>This is out-of-contract pricing, and it's one of the quietest leaks in the UK household budget. Once your initial term ends — typically 12 or 18 months — providers move you to a standard rate that's often 30–50% higher than what you were paying. The notification arrives as a line item on a bill you probably don't read carefully.</p>

<h4>Why it's so easy to miss</h4>

<p>The increase doesn't happen all at once. It happens gradually, because your contract's end date and your billing date are different. By the time you notice, you've already been overpaying for months. And because switching broadband feels like a hassle (will there be a downtime? will the new router work? what about my email address?), most people stay.</p>

<p>The CMA identified out-of-contract pricing as one of the clearest examples of the loyalty penalty in action. In broadband alone, the premium can add up to £240 a year or more for customers who've been with the same provider for several years.</p>

<h4>The regulator's response</h4>

<p>Ofcom now requires providers to notify customers when their contract is ending and highlight the best available deals. The rules helped, but they rely on the same assumption: that customers will see the notification, understand it, and act on it. The data suggests many still don't.</p>

